I don&#39;t think that R supports non-memory resident dataframes (as standard anyway).  So if the data doesn&#39;t fit into R&#39;s memory, you can&#39;t use R&#39;s &quot;dbWriteTable&quot;.

It doesn&#39;t look like you are doing statistical transforms or anything like that inside R, so you perhaps should just use psql&#39;s \copy.  Then you will miss out on fread&#39;s inference of delimiter and types, so this may take some fiddling to get it to work exactly the same.  

    psql -c &#39;\copy &quot;My_data&quot; from /myfile&#39;

Also, it looks like dbWriteTable will create the table if it does not already exist, which \copy does not do, so that will take some more fiddling.

&gt; I tried to charge directly the tsv file through the PostGre interface but it is not working with tsv file (only csv apprently) ;

You have not shown us anything that would enable us to help you with this problem.  What did you try?  What error did you get?  Does your file need escaping, and if so how is it done?  With COPY or \copy, you can either use text format (which uses backslashes to escape things which need escaping), or you can use CSV format but then specify a tab as delimiter `with (format csv, delimiter E&#39;\t&#39;)`, in which case special characters are escaped by quoting them rather than backwhacking them.

